  "meta": {
    "title": "Coral Bleaching: Vibrio Invasion of the Mucus Layer",
    "date": "2026-07-21",
    "lesson": "Rising seawater temperature stresses reef corals and weakens their protective mucus microbiome, allowing opportunistic pathogens like Vibrio coralliilyticus to bloom and degrade coral tissue. This scenario models a shallow reef flat during a marine heatwave: warm, oxygen-rich, sunlit water by day and a smaller nighttime dip. Coral-mucus organic matter is protein- and carbohydrate-rich (mucopolysaccharides and glycoproteins), so protease and carbohydrase activity are the keys to feeding. Grazing amoeba-like protists and phage that hunt the bacterial population add realistic top-down pressure, illustrating how thermal stress tips a stable symbiosis into dysbiosis.",
    "citation": "Ben-Haim et al. 2003, Vibrio coralliilyticus coral pathogen; Bourne et al. 2009 reef microbiome shifts during bleaching",
    "difficulty": "normal",
    "realWorldBasis": "Great Barrier Reef marine heatwave bleaching event, shallow reef flat"
  },
